blog.name: fitness-journey-of-a-fat-girl
blog.title: Everyday Is A New Day
blog.description: I’m a 23 year old college student who has struggled with weight my whole life. Recently my mother was diagnosed with diabetes and I had my own “pre-diabetic” scare. I was also diagnosed with PCOS and some mental illness. I’ve been eating the recommended diabetic carb intake since 9/12/18. I have also been a vegetarian for seven years now and I’m allergic to gluten. I have a long way to go and wanted to keep a blog of my journey! Even if I’m the only one reading this I want to be able to look back on my progress. However, I hope you come along for the ride and get something out of this! :)

summary: Weigh in - Month 5 (Week 22)
body:
Weigh in - Month 5 (Week 22)

SW - 267.8 - 9/12/18

CW - 232.8 - 2/13/19

Goal for Graduation - 217.8 (-50 total)

How far away from goal - 15 pounds

How much more time I have - 12 weeks

Loss this week - 1 pound

Loss total - 35 pounds


Wow! I can’t believe it’s been five months. Look how far I’ve come! I’m so proud of myself for getting this far and keeping up with my health for this long. I’m not sure I’ll hit the -15 pounds in 12 weeks for graduation but I’ll be SO close and honestly I think any continued progress is something to be insanely proud of.

summary: The 10 simple habits that helped me get healthier one day at a time
title: The 10 simple habits that helped me get healthier one day at a time
body:
The 10 simple habits that helped me get healthier one day at a time

When getting healthy, we often think of difficult, pain-in-the-a** routines. We dump bad habits like a bad date and expect the new ones to stick — but, cultivating healthy habits are actually easier to cultivate little-by-little.

Check out these 10 simple healthy habits you can build into the routine you already have, easily. Your body will thank you for it — and so will your schedule.

question: (1/?) Hey warrior female long time listener first time caller and all that.  So very recently I've come to realization that I'm transgender and it's been quite the life changer to say the least. I've always viewed my body as far too masculine and it's always brought me dissatisfaction once I discovered that that feeling has a word for it and what that word entailed it led to ALOT of realizations REAL quick needless to say but the reason I am sending this is because I don't know how to view
answer:
(2/2) my body from a fitness or health point of view anymore I feel so lost In some many areas and I’d really appreciate any advice you could give. Sincerely Trans in Trouble 

Dear Trans in Trouble, 

First off, everyone can view their body from a fitness or health point of view in the same way. If the exercise you do makes you feel better and you enjoy it (no matter what it is, even a walk in the park) then you are doing something healthy and good for you. If you are making progress (lifting greater amounts of weight, going for longer workouts or runs etc) then that’s something to view with pride. 

@thenonbinarywarrior has a blog where you might be able to view some info much more relevant to your situation. 

Do any followers have additional/more specific advice? 

-FemaleWarrior
